{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "It is axiomatic for most African scholars that the colonizers are responsible for the present problems facing the African continent.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "This paper accepts this fact but insists that the African as a human being with free will and responsibility cannot continue to blame the colonizers when he has choice either to reject the colonial predetermined events or to accept them taking responsibility for his actions.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "According to this principle, one is morally responsible for his actions only when there are alternative choices available to him.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "Following this principle, two theories are often considered in discussions about moral responsibility and freedom.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "The first is libertarianism and the second which is very common among ethical philosophers is compatibilism.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "With a preference for compatibilism, this paper will show that the African, though rendered unfree as declared by Dukor, is not totally bereft of free will and therefore to that extent should be morally responsible for his actions that continue to dehumanize him.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "African unfreedom is therefore her 'lack of the capacity to choose, act and decide for herself what or what not to do (freedom to) and the capacity for cultural, political, economic and psychological independence (freedom from)' (Dukor, 2012: p. 50).",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "The African incapacitating constraints include a barrage of issues emanating outside the African continent which make it difficult for her to organise, rule, and fashion out her life and future according to her desired choices.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "While agreeing with Dukor that the freedom denied the African is responsible for most of her present woes, this paper is intended to show that the African is as well culpable and therefore morally responsible for most of her problems.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "The African should not be exonerated from most of her woes, even though true to Dukor's stand, the greater responsibility should go the colonizers.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "To be morally responsible for one's actions is to have the power to be the ultimate creator of one's intentional acts or behaviour.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "The state of things in Africa is never an accident of history. It is a historically designed legacy of turmoil left behind by the conquerors.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "The colonizers came to Africa with some positive values but these were distorted because of their selfish intent.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "The African was made to throw away his nature, his real self and then wear the European cloak.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "None of her cultural, religious, political and social values were considered equal to the 'gifts' coming from the colonizers.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "Following this kind of manipulation, the situation of the African on the exit of the colonizers rather than changing to the status of freedom, changed to the status of 'neo-freedom'.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "The African though free in general terms to choose the course of his future, is subtly dependent on the colonizers who now dictates what he is to choose by indirect political, economic and social manipulations.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "The most fatal reason for the African problems is not the activity of the colonizers but the activity of her government and leaders.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "They have a number of options in which they were to lead Africa to a glorious future but ignored these options to pursue selfish interests such that they 'emerged as worst nightmares to the advancement of the African person' (Chihuri, 2012).",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "African problems today have little to do with the colonial legacies.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU21": {
      "text": "Her problems lie in the defective political and economic systems established by the African leaders after independence.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU22": {
      "text": "Compatibilism allows for a free marriage of the ideas of determinism and free will and hold that it is possible to believe both without being logically inconsistent.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU23": {
      "text": "The African as human a being has a free will. Her decision to continue in the colonial set agenda is her choice and she should therefore be morally responsible for whatever comes out of it.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
